      "writtenOn": "2020-10-05T16:21:07Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "should this be x_num_fds_per_item \u003d nfds / nthreads instead?\n\nthis rebalances based on making it so that the number of fds per thread is calculated based on nfds / work, instead of leaving a few remainders at the end, and then we spawn nwork threads.\n\nbut shouldn\u0027t it be balanced based on the number of threads we want in the first place? Which can be determined based on a combination of experiment plus spawning more threads of there are to many fds.\n\nalso, if we have more threads started in the beginning, does it make the broadcast any faster?",
      "revId": "087a768d596835281c115d0100c3f82fbfa87961",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "55e51532_5cf8d857",
        "filename": "util/oslib-win32poll.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 85,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-10-05T16:23:49Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "in any case i think the number of threads to wait should be explicitly specified, as that impacts overall resource footprint (also see android/base/threads/ThreadPool.h for ideas plus if it can be used)",
      "parentUuid": "2fa73f2c_416ff872",
      "revId": "087a768d596835281c115d0100c3f82fbfa87961",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "26eaa695_91f0d814",
        "filename": "util/oslib-win32poll.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 85,
      "author": {
        "id": 1046320
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-10-05T16:43:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "from my experience testing this on windows, here is the lessons\n1. if fds \u003c\u003d 64, use the calling thread is fastest;\n2. if fds \u003e 64 but \u003c\u003d128, 2 is fastest; more threads wont help, as the\nfired events are sparse; this is the case when modem simulator is on, 82\nto be exact. (75 on linux/mac).\n\nso the number of threads are most likely 2.\n\nhere I propose to do it this way:\n1. when fds \u003c\u003d64, use the old implementation (as is done in this cl, oslib-win32.c)\n2. fires 2 dedicated threads that will cover 65 to 120 (inclusing).\n3. more than that use std::async to let the system to handle (either fire up new\nor use system threads)\n\nthe devideWork tries to use as fewer threads as possible, that is the reason for the logic here\nfor the case of 82 fd,\nit let first thread handles 60, second 22, then rebalance the work load\nto 41 and 41.",
      "parentUuid": "55e51532_5cf8d857",
      "revId": "087a768d596835281c115d0100c3f82fbfa87961",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "10882600_a00257d8",
        "filename": "util/oslib-win32poll.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 85,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-10-05T17:05:02Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "thanks! let\u0027s have these comments in the code itself so people know why it\u0027s this way.\n\nbut why not start more threads in response to more than 120 instead of using std::async? that could lead to mysterious performance problems that are hard to debug down the line due to std::async slowness + more work to repro \u003e 120 fds",
      "parentUuid": "26eaa695_91f0d814",
      "revId": "087a768d596835281c115d0100c3f82fbfa87961",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
